{
  "doc_id": "24363",
  "text": "Despite the attractiveness of the callosal pathway as the most straightforward explanation of the observed effect of muscimolinactivation on ipsilateral eye input to V1, other sources must also be considered given the existence of massive descending and feedback projections connecting the cortex and thalamus. Traditionally, pathways connecting the cortex and the thalamus have been considered as unilateral reciprocal loops, although bilateral projections were described in e. g. the motor cortex [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] . For the cat visual cortex, descending bilateral projections to the thalamus have been shown with large tracer injections [CITATION_7] . Therefore contralateral cortico-thalamo-cortical pathways may mediate interhemispheric communication.",
